{
    "name": "Dire Hyena (Hyaenodon)",
    "type": "monster",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Ecology",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "<b>Environment</b> warm plains<br/><b>Organization</b> solitary, pair, or pack (3\u20138)<br/><b>Treasure</b> incidental"
        },
        {
            "name": "Description",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "Dire hyenas (known to many as hyaenodons) are more fearsome than their smaller cousins. While hyaenodons won\u2019t turn down carrion as a handy meal, they much prefer to hunt for prey. A pack of dire hyenas rarely stops moving and hunting for anything other than sleep, mating, or food. Hyaenodons are 6 feet tall at the shoulder and often over 12 feet long. They weigh 900 pounds.<br/><br/>Gnolls have been known to train hyaenodons to serve in their lairs as guardians, or more commonly as fearsome mounts."
        }
    ],
    "html": "<i>This large hyena has a thick head, rheumy red eyes, and a mouth filled with sharp, powerful teeth.</i>",
